         <OBJECT_CONTRACT>
            <TITLE>
               <P>Malawi - Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) prevention and response programme</P>
            </TITLE>
            <REFERENCE_NUMBER>8184</REFERENCE_NUMBER>
            <CPV_MAIN>
               <CPV_CODE CODE="75211200"/>
            </CPV_MAIN>
            <TYPE_CONTRACT CTYPE="SERVICES"/>
            <SHORT_DESCR>
               <P>DFID Malawi seeks to appoint an appropriately qualified supplier to manage and deliver the VAWG Programme.</P>
               <P>The objective of this programme is to reduce violence against women and girls and to improve the justice system for women and girls living with violence. It has three outcomes:</P>
               <P>- Formal and informal justice services are accessible, responsive and accountable to women and children’s needs;</P>
               <P>- People in target areas are less tolerant of violence and are more supportive of survivors;</P>
               <P>- Individuals and local institutions use non-violent means to settle disputes and avoid harmful practices.</P>
            </SHORT_DESCR>
            <VAL_ESTIMATED_TOTAL CURRENCY="GBP">22800000.00</VAL_ESTIMATED_TOTAL>
            <NO_LOT_DIVISION/>
            <OBJECT_DESCR ITEM="1">
               <n2016:NUTS CODE="UKM95"/>
               <SHORT_DESCR>
                  <P>The Programme will be delivered in two phases. In the first phase (years 1-3), the Supplier will develop, test and adapt, the comprehensive local level package(s) of GBV prevention and response interventions in different community contexts. The package of interventions would help to shift social norms and help to ensure improved justice outcomes for women and child survivors of GBV/VAC. The approaches/ models in these prevention and response packages will vary across impact areas as they will depend on what is already happening in the impact areas. These will be rigorously evaluated and the most successful package of interventions will be scaled up in the second phase (years 4-6). National level interventions will seek to improve justice outcomes of VAWG survivors.</P>
                  <P>For additional details including on scope, please refer to the terms of reference.</P>
               </SHORT_DESCR>
               <AC_PROCUREMENT_DOC/>
               <DURATION TYPE="MONTH">72</DURATION>
               <NO_RENEWAL/>
               <NB_MIN_LIMIT_CANDIDATE>5</NB_MIN_LIMIT_CANDIDATE>
               <NB_MAX_LIMIT_CANDIDATE>8</NB_MAX_LIMIT_CANDIDATE>
               <CRITERIA_CANDIDATE>
                  <P>Mandatory and discretionary exclusion, economic and financial standing, technical and professional ability, modern slavery act 2015 requirements, tenderers past performance, duty of care, international aid transparency initiative, acceptance of DFID Terms and conditions,</P>
                  <P>Also, refer para 22 (Technical Evaluation Criteria and Weighting) of the SQ Supplier Information and Instructions Document.</P>
               </CRITERIA_CANDIDATE>
               <NO_ACCEPTED_VARIANTS/>
               <OPTIONS/>
               <OPTIONS_DESCR>
                  <P>The total budget available for this contract is £ 19 000 000 (inclusive of any applicable tax) covering a duration of 72 months. Subject to need assessment, review recommendations and satisfactory performance of the Supplier, extensions could be exercised for up to 24 months with an estimated value of £ 3 800 000 (inclusive of any applicable tax).</P>
               </OPTIONS_DESCR>
               <NO_EU_PROGR_RELATED/>
               <INFO_ADD>
                  <P>This contract will be governed by English Law. Prices are not required at the 'Standard Selection Questionnaire(SQ) stage, however, when required, prices must be quoted in GBP. All payments for the contract will be made in GBP Sterling. DFID reserves the right to annul the process at any point and not award the contract.</P>
               </INFO_ADD>
            </OBJECT_DESCR>
